<doc id="359097" wikidata="Q7922660" url="?curid=359097" title="Verse paragraph">
<text>Verse paragraphs are stanzas with no regular number of lines or groups of lines that make up units of sense. They are usually separated by blank lines. It stands for a group of lines in a poem that form a rhetorical unit similar to that of a prose paragraph.

Milton&#x27;s &quot;Paradise Lost&quot; and Wordsworth&#x27;s &quot;The Prelude&quot; consist of verse paragraphs.

Verse paragraphs are frequently used in blank verse and in free verse.

